==Diary of the season==
17 June 2011: Former [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] manager [[Alex McLeish]] is appointed manager of [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref name=McLeishVilla>{{cite web|title=Aston Villa appoint Alex McLeish as manager|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/13770519|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

4 July 2011: {{fc|Manchester City}} sign full-back [[Ga<U+00EB>l Clichy]] from Arsenal for <U+00A3>7 million.<ref name="Clichy, Ga<U+00EB>l">{{cite web |url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/gael-clichy-joins-manchester-city |title=Clichy completes move to Manchester City| date=4 July 2011|accessdate=1 July 2011|publisher=Arsenal F.C. }}</ref>

6 July 2011: [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]], who were members of the Football League from to 2001 to 2006, are expelled from the Conference National due to financial problems.<ref>{{cite news|last=Doyle |first=Geoff |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14034978.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Demise of the Diamonds <U+2013> where did it all go wrong? |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-07-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110727205135/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14034978.stm| archivedate= 27 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

11 July 2011: Arsenal make their second summer signing, [[Gervinho]] from French champions [[Lille OSC|Lille]] for <U+00A3>11 million.<ref name="Gervinho contract">{{cite web|url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/gervinho-agrees-deal-to-join-arsenal |title=Gervinho agrees deal to join Arsenal| date=11 July 2011|accessdate=11 July 2011|publisher= Arsenal F.C. }}</ref>

13 July 2011: {{fc|Wolverhampton Wanderers}} sign defender [[Roger Johnson (footballer)|Roger Johnson]] from Birmingham City for an undisclosed fee, believed to have surpassed the <U+00A3>7 million the [[Black Country]] club paid for [[Steven Fletcher (footballer)|Steven Fletcher]] last summer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14104644.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Roger Johnson completes move from Birmingham to Wolves |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-07-13 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

30 July 2011: {{fc|Brighton & Hove Albion}} finally move into their [[Amex Stadium]] at [[Falmer]], first planned in 1999, and open their new home with a 3<U+2013>2 friendly defeat to {{fc|Tottenham Hotspur}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-14352820 |title=BBC News <U+2013> Spurs friendly opens Brighton's Falmer stadium |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2011-07-30 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

5 August 2011: [[Football League]] action kicks off at the [[KC Stadium]], where [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] lose 1<U+2013>0 at home to {{fc|Blackpool}} in the Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14337494.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Hull 0<U+2013>1 Blackpool |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-04 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

6 August 2011: The bulk of the opening Football League fixtures are played. [[Michael Chopra]] scores twice on his {{fc|Ipswich Town}} debut in the Championship as the [[Suffolk]] side win 3<U+2013>0 at {{fc|Bristol City}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14351931.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Bristol City 0<U+2013>3 Ipswich |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> Brighton's first competitive match at their new stadium sees them beat {{fc|Doncaster Rovers}} 2<U+2013>1 with two late goals from [[Will Buckley (footballer)|Will Buckley]] overturning a Doncaster lead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14351901.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Brighton 2<U+2013>1 Doncaster |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> League Cup holders {{fc|Birmingham City}} lose 2<U+2013>1 at {{fc|Derby County}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14352007.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Derby 2<U+2013>1 Birmingham |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> [[Steve McClaren]]'s first game in charge of {{fc|Nottingham Forest}} sees them draw 0<U+2013>0 at home to {{fc|Barnsley}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14352043.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Nott'm Forest 0<U+2013>0 Barnsley |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> Newly promoted {{fc|Southampton}} beat [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] 3<U+2013>1 at [[St Mary's Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Dawkes |first=Phil |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/14351913.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Southampton 3<U+2013>1 Leeds |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> In League One, [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] triumph 3<U+2013>0 at home to [[A.F.C. Bournemouth]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/14351895.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Charlton 3<U+2013>0 Bournemouth |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] get off to a winning start in their quest for a return to the Championship by beating [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] 2<U+2013>0 at [[Boundary Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/14352031.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Oldham 0<U+2013>2 Sheffield Utd |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> In League Two, [[Paolo Di Canio]] gets off to a winning start as [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] manager as he guides the [[Wiltshire]] club to a 3<U+2013>0 home win over [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/14351995.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Swindon 3<U+2013>0 Crewe |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> [[Crawley Town F.C.|Crawley Town's]] first Football League game sees them draw 2<U+2013>2 with [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] at [[Vale Park]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/14352019.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Port Vale 2<U+2013>2 Crawley Town |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref> [[AFC Wimbledon]], formed nine years ago in response to the [[Relocation of Wimbledon F.C. to Milton Keynes|relocation]] of [[Wimbledon F.C.|the old]] Wimbledon club (rebranded as [[Milton Keynes Dons F.C.|Milton Keynes Dons]] in June 2004) to [[Milton Keynes]], start their Football League career with a 3<U+2013>2 home defeat to [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/14351943.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> AFC Wimbledon 2<U+2013>3 Bristol R |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-06 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

7 August 2011: Manchester United win the [[FA Community Shield]], beating neighbours [[Manchester City F.C.|City]] 3<U+2013>2 at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] after going 2<U+2013>0 down.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bevan |first=Chris |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14420151.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Manchester City 2<U+2013>3 Manchester United |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-07 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

8 August 2011: [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] sign 17-year-old winger [[Alex Oxlade-Chamberlain]] from [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] for <U+00A3>12million, which could eventually rise to <U+00A3>15million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14448089.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Arsenal sign Alex Oxlade-Chamberlain from Southampton |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-08 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

11 August 2011: Tottenham Hotspur's opening Premier League game of the season, against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 13 August, is postponed due to [[2011 England riots|recent rioting]] in and near the [[Tottenham]] area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14485169.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Tottenham v Everton postponed but rest of Premier League on |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-11 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

12 August 2011: [[Kenny Dalglish]] makes his fifth signing of the close season for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] with a <U+00A3>6million move for [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] defender [[Jos<U+00E9> Enrique S<U+00E1>nchez|Jose Enrique]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14494213.stm |title=BBC Sport <U+2013> Jose Enrique joins Liverpool from Newcastle |publisher=BBC News |date=2011-08-12 |accessdate=2011-08-24}}</ref>

15 August 2011: [[Cesc F<U+00E0>bregas]] leaves [[Arsenal F.C.]] to return to his former club [[F.C. Barcelona|Barcelona]] for <U+00A3>35million.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/arsenal-agree-terms-with-barca-for-fabregas |title=Arsenal agree terms with barca for fabregas  | date=15 August 2011|accessdate=15 August 2011|publisher=Arsenal F.C. }}</ref>

16 August 2011: [[Emmanuel Ebou<U+00E9>]] leaves [[Arsenal F.C.]] to join Turkish side [[Galatasaray]] for <U+00A3>3 million.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,11670_7106257,00.html |title=Galatasaray sign Eboue |work=Sky Sports}}</ref>

24 August 2011: [[Samir Nasri]] joins [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] from [[Arsenal F.C.]] for <U+00A3>25 million.<ref name="Nasri">{{cite news |url=http://www.arsenal.com/news/news-archive/terms-agreed-with-man-city-for-nasri |title=Terms agreed with Manchester City for Nasri | date=23 August 2011|accessdate=23 August 2011|publisher=Arsenal F.C. }}</ref> [[Juan Mata]] joins [[Chelsea F.C.]] from [[Valencia CF]] for <U+00A3>23.5million.<ref name="Mata">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14656464.stm |title=Juan Mata completes move to Chelsea from Valencia |work=BBC Football | date=24 August 2011}}</ref>

29 August 2011: [[Edin D<U+017E>eko]] scores four goals as [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] briefly go top of the Premier League with a 5<U+2013>1 thrashing of [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Tottenham 1 - 5 Man City|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14606056|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>  though they are soon usurped at the top of the table on goal difference by their rivals Manchester United, who demolish [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 8<U+2013>2 at [[Old Trafford]]. The result is Arsenal's worst for 116 years and United biggest goal haul in a league game since February 1999.<ref>{{cite web|title=Man Utd 8 - 2 Arsenal|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14606020|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

31 August 2011: August ends with reigning champions Manchester United top of the table on goal difference, ahead of Manchester City. Liverpool. Chelsea, Wolverhampton Wanderers, Newcastle United and Aston Villa complete the top seven, with West Bromwich Albion, Blackburn Rovers and Tottenham Hotspur (all without a point) in the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barclays Premier League 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 August|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/PR/toaug.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>  In the Championship, newly promoted Brighton and Hove Albion and Southampton occupy the automatic promotion places, with Derby County, Middlesbrough, West Ham United and Crystal Palace in the playoff places.<ref>{{cite web|title=npower Football League Championship 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 August|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/D1/toaug.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

1 September 2011: The transfer window closes with [[Mikel Arteta]] ending six years at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] to sign for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in a <U+00A3>10 million deal.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14744368.stm | work=BBC News | title=Arteta defends timing of transfer | date=1 September 2011}}</ref> [[Ars<U+00E8>ne Wenger]] also brings [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea's]] [[Yossi Benayoun]] to the [[Emirates Stadium]], on a loan deal for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14739185.stm | work=BBC News | title=Arsenal sign Arteta and Benayoun | date=31 August 2011}}</ref> These acquisitions come 24 hours after Wenger bolsters his defence with a <U+00A3>6.2 million move for [[Fenerbah<U+00E7>e]] and [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] left-back [[Andr<U+00E9> Santos]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14712232.stm | work=BBC News | title=Brazil defender moves to Arsenal | date=31 August 2011}}</ref> Another big money move on deadline day includes [[Raul Meireles]] leaving Liverpool in a <U+00A3>10 million move to Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-14742223 | work=BBC News | title=English Premier League summer spending hits <U+00A3>485m | date=1 September 2011}}</ref> Having left Manchester United at the end of last season after four injury-plagued seasons, [[Owen Hargreaves]] signs for neighbours Manchester City on a one-year contract,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14717296.stm | work=BBC News | title=Hargreaves ready to take his time | date=1 September 2011}}</ref> after weeks of speculation that he would join [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14503439.stm | work=BBC News | title=Albion close on Hargreaves deal | date=19 August 2011}}</ref> [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] terminate the contract of striker [[El Hadji Diouf]] after two years at [[Ewood Park]],<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14748844.stm | work=BBC News | title=Diouf's Blackburn deal terminated | date=1 September 2011}}</ref> where the attack was strengthened the previous day by the arrival of Everton's out-of-favour striker [[Yakubu]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14731140.stm | work=BBC News | title=Yakubu makes switch to Blackburn | date=31 August 2011}}</ref>

8 September 2011: [[Dagenham & Redbridge F.C.]] contest a [[Football League Trophy]] Round One match against [[Leyton Orient]] at [[The Matchroom Stadium]]. With the scores level at 1-1 after 90 minutes, the match goes to penalties and as a result become the longest penalty shoot out with consecutive goalscorers in the history of English football and what is believed to be the world. The final score ended as 14-13 to Dagenham on penalties, with [[Ben Chorley]] missing the 28th spot kick for Orient which sent the Daggers through to a second round clash with [[Southend United]].

30 September 2011: September ends with Manchester United still leading the Premier League, ahead of Mancunian rivals City on goal difference. Chelsea remain in third, while Newcastle United are maintaining their European push in fourth place. The top seven is rounded out by Liverpool, Tottenham Hotspur and Stoke City. Blackburn Rovers, West Bromwich Albion and Bolton Wanderers are still suffering from their early season form and make up the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barclays Premier League 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 30 September|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/PR/tosep.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> In the Championship, newly promoted Southampton are continuing their bid for successive promotions, leading Middlesbrough and Derby County on goal difference. West Ham United, Brighton & Hove Albion and Cardiff City complete the top six, while Millwall, Bristol City and Doncaster Rovers stand at the foot of the table.<ref>{{cite web|title=npower Football League Championship 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 30 September|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/D1/tosep.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

23 October 2011: Manchester City extend their lead over Manchester United at the top of the Premier League with a 6<U+2013>1 win over their local rivals at Old Trafford. It was Manchester United's worst loss at Old Trafford since 1955 and the first time they had conceded six goals at home since 1930.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester United 1 <U+2013> 6 Manchester City |last=McNulty |first=Phil |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/15325536 |work=BBC Sport |date=23 October 2011 |accessdate=2012-02-17}}</ref> Fellow title contenders Chelsea suffer a 1<U+2013>0 setback against Queen's Park Rangers at [[Loftus Road]].

29 October 2011: [[Robin van Persie]] scores a hat-trick as Arsenal gain a first away league win of the season, beating Chelsea 5<U+2013>3 at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].

31 October 2011: October ends with Manchester City 5 points clear of second-placed Manchester United. Newcastle United continue to defy critics who tipped them to struggle this season and stand in third place, while the top seven is rounded out by Chelsea, Tottenham Hotspur, Liverpool and an ever-improving Arsenal side who appear to have put their poor start to the season behind them. At the other end of the table, Wigan Athletic stand bottom after six successive losses; they are joined in the relegation zone by Blackburn Rovers and Bolton Wanderers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barclays Premier League 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 October|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/PR/tooct.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> In the Championship, Southampton are continuing their bid to become the second team in two seasons to achieve two successive promotion to the Premier League, standing three points clear of second-placed West Ham United. Crystal Palace, expected by many to struggle this season, are three points behind West Ham in third, while the play-off places are completed by Middlesbrough, Derby County and Hull City. Coventry City, Doncaster Rovers and Bristol City make up the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web|title=npower Football League Championship 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 October|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/D1/tooct.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

18 November 2011: League One side Carlisle United announce plans to relocate from [[Brunton Park]], their home since 1909, to a new 12,000-seat stadium.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15788028.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carlisle reveal ground move plans | date=18 November 2011}}</ref>

27 November 2011: Football mourns the death of Wales manager [[Gary Speed]], 42, who was found dead at his home in [[Chester]]. Speed, who had managed the Welsh side for nearly a year following a brief spell as manager of Sheffield United, was a player in the English leagues for more than 20 years, during which time he won a league title with Leeds United and was an FA Cup runner-up twice with Newcastle United.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-15911321 | work=BBC News | title=Footballing world pays tribute to Gary Speed | date=28 November 2011}}</ref>

28 November 2011: Queen's Park Rangers chairman [[Tony Fernandes]] announces his intention to relocate the club from [[Loftus Road]] to a new, bigger stadium elsewhere in [[West (London sub region)|West London]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15919454.stm | work=BBC News | title=QPR looking to leave Loftus Road | date=28 November 2011}}</ref>

30 November 2011: Sunderland manager [[Steve Bruce]] becomes the first Premiership manager to be sacked during the season, leaving the north-east club after two-and-a-half years in charge with the Wearside club only two points clear of the relegation zone. The month ends with Manchester City still five points clear of Manchester United. Tottenham Hotspur have put their poor start firmly behind and stand two points behind United with a game in hand. Newcastle occupy the crucial fourth place, while Chelsea have slipped out of the top four after losing three of their last five matches. Liverpool and Arsenal complete the top seven. The relegation zone remains unchanged, except that Wigan Athletic have moved off the bottom of the table at the expense of Blackburn Rovers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barclays Premier League 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 30 November|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/PR/tonov.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> Southampton and West Ham United continue to occupy the automatic promotion places in the Championship, while Cardiff City, Middlesbrough, Leeds United and Leicester City (ahead of seventh-placed Brighton on goal difference) make up the playoff zone. Doncaster Rovers and Coventry City remain joint bottom of the Championship, while Nottingham Forest have dropped back into the relegation zone, behind Portsmouth, Bristol City and Ipswich Town on goal difference.<ref>{{cite web|title=npower Football League Championship 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 30 November|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/D1/tonov.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

6 December 2011: Chelsea join Arsenal in the knockout stages of the Champions League with a 3<U+2013>0 home win over [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] in their final group game, to ease the pressure on under-fire manager Andr<U+00E9> Villas-Boas after four wins from the previous 10 games in all competitions led to increased speculation about his future as manager.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/15933202.stm | work=BBC News | title=Chelsea 3<U+2013>0 Valencia | date=6 December 2011}}</ref>

7 December 2011: Manchester United's 2<U+2013>1 defeat at [[FC Basel]] in Switzerland knocks them out of the Champions League and puts them into the Europa League.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15956703.stm | work=BBC News | title=FC Basel 2<U+2013>1 Man Utd | date=7 December 2011}}</ref> Their neighbours Manchester City suffer a similar fate despite their 2<U+2013>0 home win over [[Bayern Munich]] in their final group game.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/15956717.stm | work=BBC News | title=Manchester City 2<U+2013>0 Bayern Munich | date=7 December 2011}}</ref>

31 December 2011: The year ends with Manchester United joint top of the Premier League after having overcome City's five-point lead, although City have a game in hand. Tottenham Hotspur remain in third, six points adrift of United but with a game in hand, while Arsenal have moved into the crucial fourth place for the first time this season, at the expense of Chelsea. Liverpool and Newcastle complete the top seven. Bolton Wanderers end the year bottom of the Premier League; Blackburn Rovers (who were bottom on Christmas) and Wigan Athletic remain in the relegation zone, although the pressure is building up on Wolverhampton Wanderers and QPR.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barclays Premier League 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 December|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/PR/todec.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> In the Championship, Southampton remain top and still well placed for a second successive promotion. Middlesbrough now occupy second, while West Ham United, Cardiff City, Reading and Hull City complete the top six. The relegation zone remains unchanged from end of November.<ref>{{cite web|title=npower Football League Championship 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 December|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/D1/todec.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

31 January 2012: January ends with Manchester City still top of the Premier League, but with United now level on points with them, five points ahead of third-place Tottenham. Chelsea, Liverpool, Arsenal and Newcastle complete the top seven. Wigan are bottom of the table, four points adrift of safety, while Wolves and Blackburn are just a single point adrift.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchesterunited-mad.co.uk/snapshot_tables/2011_2012/31/jan/manchester_united/index.shtml |title=Snapshot Tables 2011-2012 31 Jan Manchester United - Manchester United FC - United Mad |publisher=Manchesterunited-mad.co.uk |date=2012-01-31 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> West Ham are now top of the Championship, with Southampton, Cardiff, Birmingham, Hull and Blackpool completing the top six. Coventry (last), Nottingham Forest and Doncaster Rovers remain in the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web|title=npower Football League Championship 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 January|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/D1/tojan.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

3 February 2012: Chelsea and England captain [[John Terry]], awaiting trial on a charge of racially abusing QPR's [[Anton Ferdinand]] in a league game on 21 December, is stripped of the England captaincy.<ref>{{cite web|author=10:56 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16866149 |title=BBC Sport - John Terry: FA strips England captaincy from Chelsea defender |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-02-03 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

6 February 2012: England coach [[Fabio Capello]] criticises the decision of the [[Football Association]] to strip John Terry of the England captaincy.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16902987 | work=BBC News | title=Capello speaks out on Terry decision | date=6 February 2012}}</ref>

8 February 2012: Tottenham manager [[Harry Redknapp]] and the former [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] chairman [[Milan Mandari<U+0107>]] are cleared of tax evasion after a trial at [[Southwark]] [[Crown Court]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-16925280 | work=BBC News | title=Harry Redknapp cleared of tax evasion | date=8 February 2012}}</ref> Hours after the verdicts are delivered, England coach Fabio Capello announces his immediate resignation<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-16957737 | work=BBC News | title=Fabio Capello quits as England manager | date=8 February 2012}}</ref> and almost immediately there are widespread calls across football for Redknapp to be installed as Capello's successor.<ref>{{cite web|author=21:40 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16969777 |title=BBC Sport - Harry Redknapp is the right man for England, says Alan Shearer |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

12 February 2012: The [[Black Country derby]] sees West Bromwich Albion crush Wolverhampton Wanderers 5<U+2013>1 at the Molineux.

13 February 2012: Less than 24 hours after the Black Country derby humiliation, Wolverhampton Wanderers sack manager [[Mick McCarthy]], their manager for five-and-a-half years.<ref>{{cite web|author=17:04 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17012933 |title=BBC Sport - Mick McCarthy sacked as Wolves manager after West Brom defeat |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-02-13 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

24 February 2012: After [[Alan Curbishley]] and [[Walter Smith]] both rejected the chance to manage Wolverhampton Wanderers, coach [[Terry Connor]] is put in charge of the first team until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|author=11:41 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17153404 |title=BBC Sport - Terry Connor named Wolves manager until end of season |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-02-24 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

26 February 2012: [[Kenny Dalglish]] wins the first trophy of his second spell as Liverpool manager, as they defeat Cardiff City on penalties after a 2<U+2013>2 draw in the League Cup final <U+2013> the first time they have won the trophy under the management of Dalglish, who guided them to three league titles and two FA Cups in his first spell as manager.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bevan |first=Chris |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17174308 |title=BBC Sport - Kenny Dalglish believes Carling Cup win can inspire Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-02-26 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

29 February 2012: February ends with Manchester City two points clear of Manchester United in second and 10 points clear of Tottenham Hotspur, whose title charge now appears to be over following a 5<U+2013>2 defeat at rival Arsenal, who end the month in the crucial fourth place. Chelsea, Newcastle and Liverpool remain in the top seven. Although they remain bottom, Wigan are now only one point adrift of safety, joined in the bottom three by Bolton and Blackburn, with Wolves and QPR both within a point of the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barclays Premier League 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 29 February|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/PR/tofeb.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> Southampton are back on top of the Championship, but West Ham are a point behind with a game in hand. Reading, Blackpool, Birmingham and Cardiff make up the play-off zone. Nottingham Forest have now climbed clear of the relegation zone at the expense of a Portsmouth side deduced ten points after entering administration; the South Coast club are sandwiched by Coventry and bottom side Doncaster.<ref>{{cite web|title=npower Football League Championship 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 29 February|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/D1/tofeb.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>

4 March 2012: Chelsea sack manager Andre Villas-Boas after nine months in charge, the day after they lost 1<U+2013>0 in the league at West Bromwich Albion. It is the second time in three weeks that the [[Black Country]] side have inflicted a defeat upon a team whose manager has then been sacked. In another twist, Chelsea appoint their assistant manager [[Roberto Di Matteo]], who was sacked as Albion manager last season, in charge until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|author=13:40 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17250464 |title=BBC Sport - Villas-Boas sacked by Chelsea: AVB goes after just nine months |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-03-04 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

11 March 2012: Manchester United moved to first position in the Premier League for the first time since early October 2011 with 10 games remaining after United defeated West Bromwich Albion 2<U+2013>0 and previous leaders Manchester City loss 0<U+2013>1 to Swansea.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manchester United 2 West Brom 0|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17249251|publisher=BBC|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>

17 March 2012: The FA Cup quarter-final tie between Tottenham Hotspur and Bolton Wanderers at [[White Hart Lane]] is postponed after 41 minutes when the visiting team's midfielder [[Fabrice Muamba]] is taken seriously ill on the pitch after collapsing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17323646 |title=BBC Sport - Tottenham A-A Bolton |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-03-17 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

29 March 2012: Aston Villa captain [[Stiliyan Petrov]] is diagnosed with acute [[leukaemia]] after complaining of a fever following the club's game against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].

31 March 2012:  March ends with Manchester United now holding a two-point advantage over City, with a game in hand. The rest of the top seven remains unchanged, except that Everton have now moved ahead of their Merseyside rivals Liverpool, who are in eighth place with a game in hand. Wolves have only managed to pick up one point following the sacking of Mick McCarthy and look doomed for relegation as they stand six points adrift of safety with seven games left to play. Blackburn Rovers, with a game in hand, are ahead of QPR and Wigan only by virtue of goals scored; Bolton are a point ahead of Blackburn, having played the same number of games as their Lancashire rivals.<ref>{{cite web|title=Barclays Premier League 2011-2012 Season Domestic Stats to 26-May-12 inclusive League Table on 31 March|url=http://stats.football365.co.uk/2012/ENG/PR/tomar.html|publisher=stats.football365.co.uk|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> In the Championship, Southampton look certain for promotion as they are six points clear of third-placed West Ham with six games left, although their challenge for the Football League title is coming under threat from Reading, who stand two points behind. Birmingham (with a game in hand), Blackpool and Brighton make up the play-off places, with Middlesbrough only outside on goal difference. At the opposite end of the table, Coventry have climbed out of the drop zone at the expense of Bristol City, although Doncaster and Portsmouth look doomed for the drop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/league-championship/2011-2012/table/2012-03-31 |title=English League Championship 2011-2012 Table |publisher=statto.com |date=2012-03-31 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

14 April 2012: Charlton Athletic become the first League side to gain promotion after a 1<U+2013>0 win at Carlisle United meant that Charlton were promoted and would be playing Championship football in 2012/13 after a three-year exile. On the same day Fleetwood Town were confirmed as champions of the Football Conference meaning that as from next season they'll be playing League Football for the first time in their history.

17 April 2012: Reading are promoted back to the Premier League after a four-year exile by beating Nottingham Forest 1<U+2013>0 at home.<ref>{{cite web|author=10:01 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17753765 |title=BBC Sport - Reaction to Reading's promotion to the Premier League |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-18 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

21 April 2012: Already-relegated Doncaster Rovers drag Coventry City down to League One with them by winning 2<U+2013>0 in the Championship clash at the [[Ricoh Arena]], meaning that the midlanders will be playing third tier football next season for the first time in nearly 50 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17711663 |title=BBC Sport - Coventry 0-2 Doncaster |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-21 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> Portsmouth's relegation is also confirmed by a 2<U+2013>1 home defeat by Derby County, a mere two years after being in the Premier League and four years after winning the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17711036 |title=BBC Sport - Portsmouth 1-2 Derby |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-21 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> Rochdale become the first League One side of the season to suffer relegation, after losing 2<U+2013>1 at Chesterfield, whose victory keeps their own survival hopes alive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17711218 |title=BBC Sport - Chesterfield 2-1 Rochdale |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-21 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> Swindon Town seal promotion from League Two despite a 3<U+2013>1 defeat at Gillingham,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17711463 |title=BBC Sport - Gillingham 3-1 Swindon |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-21 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> Shrewsbury's chances of sealing promotion are put on hold by a 1<U+2013>1 draw at Accrington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17711610 |title=BBC Sport - Accrington 1-1 Shrewsbury |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-21 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

22 April 2012: Wolves are relegated from the Premier League after a three-year stay with a 2<U+2013>0 home defeat to Manchester City, whose title hopes are kept alive by Manchester United being held to a 4<U+2013>4 draw at [[Old Trafford]] by Everton.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ornstein |first=David |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17718140 |title=BBC Sport - Wolves 0-2 Manchester City |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-22 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

28 April 2012: [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] are promoted to the Premier League after a seven-year exile, achieving promotion for the second year running.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hassan |first=Nabil |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17795679 |title=BBC Sport - Southampton promoted to Premier League after beating Coventry |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-28 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> [[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] secure automatic promotion to League One.<ref>{{cite web|last=Scott |first=Ged |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17827006 |title=BBC Sport - Promotion-winning Turner sets sights on League One |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-29 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] drop back into the Conference after 15 years in the [[Football League]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Glendinning |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/macclesfield_town/s/1492414_macclesfield-town-0-burton-albion-2-macclesfield-relegated |title=Macclesfield Town 0 Burton Albion 2: Macclesfield relegated &#124; Manchester Evening News |publisher=menmedia.co.uk |date=2012-04-28 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

30 April 2012: April ends with Manchester City top of the Premier League after a 1<U+2013>0 home win over rivals Manchester United, who are level on point with City but wield an inferior goal difference <U+2013> both have two games left to play. The race for the last two Champions League places is reaching its climax, with five points separating Arsenal, Tottenham, Newcastle and Chelsea, although Arsenal have played one game more. However, should Chelsea beat Bayern Munich in the Champions League final the West London side will automatically qualify for the Champions League regardless of their final place in the table. Everton's belated challenge for European qualification is over; the sole remaining aim of the season is to finish above archrivals Liverpool, who are two points behind in eighth. Wolves have already been mathematically relegated, while Blackburn and Bolton (the latter with a game in hand) remain in the bottom three, but QPR, Wigan and Aston Villa are not yet certain of safety.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/premier-league/2011-2012/table/2012-04-30 |title=English Premier League 2011-2012 Table |publisher=statto.com |date=2012-04-30 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> In the Championship, Reading and Southampton have achieved promotion to the Premier League. West Ham, Birmingham, Blackpool and Cardiff will compete in the play-offs, while Portsmouth, Coventry and Doncaster are relegated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/league-championship/2011-2012/table |title=English League Championship 2011-2012 Table |publisher=statto.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

1 May 2012: Roy Hodgson of West Bromwich Albion is confirmed as the next England Manager.<ref>{{cite web|author=14:04 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17904713 |title=BBC Sport - Roy Hodgson appointed England manager by FA |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-05-01 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> Manchester City go top of the Premier League on goal difference with two games remaining with a 1<U+2013>0 home win over United.<ref>{{cite web|author=21:19 GMT |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17903432 |title=BBC Sport - Man City derby win changes nothing - Roberto Mancini |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-04-30 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

5 May 2012: Chelsea win the FA Cup with a 2<U+2013>1 victory over Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web|last=McNulty |first=Phil |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17878435 |title=BBC Sport - Chelsea 2-1 Liverpool |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-05-05 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> On the Final Day of the season for League One Sheffield Wednesday pipped Sheffield United to the second automatic promotion slot beating already relegated Wycombe Wanderers 2<U+2013>0,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17878339 |title=BBC Sport - Sheffield Wed 2-0 Wycombe |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-05-05 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> whilst Stevenage cemented their place in the Play-Offs with a 3<U+2013>0 victory over Bury (Huddersfield Town and Milton Keynes Dons make up the rest of Play-Off positions). In League Two Crawley Town won back to back promotions to League One with a 2<U+2013>1 victory at Accrington Stanley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17878295 |title=BBC Sport - Accrington 0-1 Crawley Town |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-05-05 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref> Southend United, Torquay United, Cheltenham Town and Crewe Alexandra make up the Play-Offs. At the other end of the table Barnet survived to fight another season in League Two after beating Burton Albion, this result condemned Hereford United to Conference Football next season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17878379 |title=BBC Sport - Hereford 3-2 Torquay |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-05-05 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

6 May 2012: Manchester City remain top of the Premier League with a 2<U+2013>0 win at Newcastle United, but their neighbours remain level on points with them by beating Swansea 2<U+2013>0 at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Magowan |first=Alistair |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17885312 |title=BBC Sport - Man Utd 2-0 Swansea |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-05-06 |accessdate=2012-07-03}}</ref>

7 May 2012: Blackburn are relegated from the Premier League after a 1<U+2013>0 home defeat to Wigan Athletic, ending an 11-year stint in the top flight <U+2013> the result confirms Wigan's Premier League status for an eighth successive season. Bolton Wanderers occupy the final remaining relegation place and need to win their final game of the season to stand any chance of survival. The only other team in real danger of relegation are QPR, as Aston Villa's much better goal difference means that they will almost certainly stay up.<ref name="bbc.co.uk">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17982892 |title=BBC Sport - Monday football |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2012-05-07 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref>

13 May 2012: Manchester City scored twice in stoppage time to be crowned champions for the first time in 44 years as they beat Queen's Park Rangers to win the Premier League on goal difference from Manchester United. In scenes of near bedlam, City looked to be suffering a dramatic collapse as QPR - safe after Stoke City drew with Bolton - held on to an unlikely advantage with United leading at Sunderland. Edin Dzeko equalised in the second of five minutes of stoppage time before Sergio Aguero scored the goal that won the title.<ref name="bbc.co.uk"/>

==New clubs==
* [[Windsor F.C.]], a new club formed and owned by fans of the defunct [[Windsor & Eton F.C.]], were accepted into the [[Combined Counties Football League|Combined Counties Football League Premier Division]] (level 9).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windsorfc.net/wfc_11.php |title=Windsor FC - History In The Making|publisher=Windsor F.C. |date= |accessdate=2013-01-02}}</ref> Their first match in the competition was a 1<U+2013>1 draw with [[South Park F.C.|South Park]].
* [[Guernsey F.C.]] were accepted into the [[Combined Counties Football League]] Division One (level 10). Their first match in the competition was a 5<U+2013>0 victory over [[Knaphill F.C.|Knaphill]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/14416928 |title=Combined Counties League: Guernsey FC 5-0 Knaphill FC |date=6 August 2011 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=12 July 2012}}</ref>

===Clubs removed===
